TY  - JOUR
T1  - Compliance with the Minimum Wage Law
AU  - Ashenfelter, Orley
AU  - Smith, Robert S.
Y1  - 1979/04/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260759
DO  - 10.1086/260759
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 333
EP  - 350
VL  - 87
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper investigates the extent and patterns of compliance with the federal minimum wage. Using a profit-maximizing model of compliance, predictions about compliance with weak or random government enforcement are made. Such enforcement is not random, however, and our measures of compliance suggest that government enforcement, while not inducing anything near complete compliance, does have an impact. Overall compliance in 1973 is estimated to be about 65 percent, while it is about 10 percentage points lower after the new minimum was established in 1975. Compliance appears highest among regional/racial/sex (but not age) groups where market incentives for violation are strongest.
AB  - This paper investigates the extent and patterns of compliance with the federal minimum wage. Using a profit-maximizing model of compliance, predictions about compliance with weak or random government enforcement are made. Such enforcement is not random, however, and our measures of compliance suggest that government enforcement, while not inducing anything near complete compliance, does have an impact. Overall compliance in 1973 is estimated to be about 65 percent, while it is about 10 percentage points lower after the new minimum was established in 1975. Compliance appears highest among regional/racial/sex (but not age) groups where market incentives for violation are strongest.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260759
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260759
Y2  - 2024/03/22
