TY  - JOUR
T1  - One-Way Arbitrage and Its Implications for the Foreign Exchange Markets
AU  - Deardorff, Alan V.
Y1  - 1979/04/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260760
DO  - 10.1086/260760
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 351
EP  - 364
VL  - 87
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The relationship between spot and forward exchange rates and domestic and foreign interest rates is examined with transactions costs in all markets. Market participants choose the least-cost method of exchanging currencies in these markets, thus engaging in one-way arbitrage if that is preferable to a direct transaction. One-way arbitrage consists of using one exchange market and the two securities markets to replace a direct transaction in the other exchange market. It is shown that one-way arbitrage should prevent rates from ever departing enough from interest parity for conventional covered interest arbitrage to break even.
AB  - The relationship between spot and forward exchange rates and domestic and foreign interest rates is examined with transactions costs in all markets. Market participants choose the least-cost method of exchanging currencies in these markets, thus engaging in one-way arbitrage if that is preferable to a direct transaction. One-way arbitrage consists of using one exchange market and the two securities markets to replace a direct transaction in the other exchange market. It is shown that one-way arbitrage should prevent rates from ever departing enough from interest parity for conventional covered interest arbitrage to break even.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260760
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260760
Y2  - 2024/03/22
